<HEADLINE>
<P>
SOUTH COAST LEAGUE GIRLS' SOCCER; MATER DEI KNOCKS OFF NO. 3 CAPISTRANO VALLEY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DAN ARRITT 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Mater Dei girls' soccer team earned some respect when the unranked 
Monarchs defeated No. 3 Capistrano Valley, 1-0, in a South Coast League game 
Thursday at Mater Dei. 
</P>
<P>
 A goal by Trisha Steiner late in the game put Mater Dei on top of the league 
standings and might help the Monarchs (13-4-1, 4-0-1) earn a spot among the top 
10. 
</P>
<P>
 For much of the game, the Cougars (15-3-3, 4-1) employed seven attackers 
inside the penalty box, leaving only three defenders at midfield. 
</P>
<P>
 However, Mater Dei sophomores Julie Peck and Sarah McEachen quickly cleared 
the ball each time the Cougars threatened. 
</P>
<P>
 With four minutes remaining, Chrissy Whalen lofted a pass from the endline 
toward the corner of the goal, where Steiner was waiting. Steiner trapped the 
ball and put it in the goal, prompting a cry of foul from Cougar Coach Harry 
Hutcheson. 
</P>
<P>
 "There is no way that girl (Steiner) was on sides," he said. "This was the 
worst job of refing I've seen. 
</P>
<P>
 "This wasn't a soccer game, it was a football game. I've got a bunch of 
walking wounded on my side." DAN ARRITT 
</P>
</TEXT>
