<HEADLINE>
<P>
VENTURA MOTHER PLEADS GUILTY TO CHILD STEALING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JEFF McDONALD, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A Ventura mother of two who fled to Sri Lanka rather than give up her children 
pleaded guilty to four felonies on Thursday, but will likely avoid prison. 
</P>
<P>
 Niki Lynn Ruberoe, 33, on Thursday admitted to charges of child stealing, 
violating a custody agreement, conspiracy and aiding and abetting failure to 
appear in court. 
</P>
<P>
 She could have received eight years in state prison for her crimes but agreed 
to the plea on the condition she receive probation. Sentencing is scheduled for 
Feb. 18. 
</P>
<P>
 Ruberoe was granted temporary custody of her two children last summer. But 
when her husband, the children's stepfather, was convicted of multiple counts 
of child molestation, she chose to take the children out of the country rather 
than return them to their biological father, Ruberoe's ex-husband. 
</P>
<P>
 Ruberoe admitted taking the children, ages 10 and 13, to France and then 
arranging for them to meet her husband, Channa Ruberoe, in Sri Lanka, where he 
is a citizen. 
</P>
<P>
 Niki Ruberoe was returned to Ventura County last month, but authorities are 
still attempting to bring back her husband, who is fighting extradition because 
he still faces sentencing on the molestation charges and would probably face 
additional penalties for failing to appear in court. 
</P>
<P>
 Defense attorney Steve P. Pell on Thursday called the plea bargain reasonable. 
</P>
<P>
 "She doesn't belong in prison," said Pell, who added that his client would be 
filing for divorce from her husband soon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
