<HEADLINE>
<P>
NO FRAUD EVIDENT IN PRUDENTIAL FUND FAILURE, WITNESS SAYS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SCOT J. PALTROW, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Expert witnesses for Prudential Securities Inc. testified Thursday that they 
had found no sign of fraud in the firm's failed, $1.44-billion oil and gas 
limited partnership program known as the Energy Income Funds. 
</P>
<P>
 "There are no villains to look for, there are no culprits," said Ben C. Ball 
Jr., an oil and gas consultant and former Gulf Oil executive. 
</P>
<P>
 The second day of a federal court hearing marked Prudential's first 
opportunity to call witnesses in open court to dispute allegations that the 
partnerships falsely promised steep returns to elderly investors and paid them 
their own money back in the guise of profits. 
</P>
<P>
 U.S. District Judge Marcel Livaudais Jr. is holding the hearing to decide if 
he should approve a class-action settlement that would pay $90.7 million to 
about 125,000 investors. 
</P>
<P>
 Ball testified that the partnerships' projections for oil and gas prices were 
in line with industry and federal government standards. He said investors lost 
money only because oil prices in the mid-1980s confounded the projections, 
plunging instead of rising. 
</P>
<P>
 The partnerships would have made money even if oil prices had been flat, Ball 
contended. "It was the unpredictable events in the oil and gas industry which 
account for all of the out-of-pocket losses of investors," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 Under cross-examination by investors' lawyer Stuart C. Goldberg, however, Ball 
acknowledged that individual Energy Income partnerships lost money even though 
they were formed during periods in the late 1980s when oil prices were rising. 
</P>
<P>
 Goldberg and Jeff D. Ferentz of Newport Beach are the only attorneys opposing 
approval of the settlement, which they argue is grossly inadequate. 
</P>
<P>
 Prudential's other expert witness, Kenneth M. Burke, a senior accountant with 
Ernst & Young and a longtime specialist in oil and gas accounting, said he had 
found nothing improper in the Energy Income funds' prospectuses or in the way 
Prudential accounted for the money paid out to investors. 
</P>
<P>
 The hearing is due to conclude today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
